{
  "answer": "**The elegy is \"Saqaliya\" (Chapter 21) from *Bang-E-Dara Part 2* by Allama Iqbal.**[^1]\n\nThis poem mourns Sicily—a Mediterranean island—as the \"grave of Hejazi civilization,\"[^2] compares the speaker's lament to the nightingale of Shiraz weeping for Baghdad and to Ibn Badrun's anguish over Granada,[^3] and closes with the promise to carry the island's sorrow \"as a gift to Hindustan.\"\n\nThe closing couplet is:\n\n> I shall carry you as a gift to Hindustan;  \n> I weep here myself, to make others weep there.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Saqaliya](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-02c3ef).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-665fb2).",
